Checking what the people behind trendy "memes" are doing nowadays is a good way to track social changes and which way the wind blows. E.g. the neckbeard guy from the DeviantArt "god i wish that were me" meme paints his beard pink and has like "he/him antifascist anarchist" in bio

The inherent dehumanization in the "becoming a meme" phenomenon places these people outside the rational agent category and makes them seem like environmental markers in the same way you can trace water pollution from mollusks or oysters. It always surprises you to check on them.

Cinemas have always struck me as very depressing places. Having to walk out immediately after the film instead of reclining and taking some time to think. The empty halls at the later hours of the night. Date couples anxious to have sex afterwards. Carrying your jacket in winter.

The entire experience feels burdened by hundreds of factors. Gimmicky 3D glasses at one point, the tickets, etc. Home cinema is simply the better way. Ideal is a laptop in bed or a desktop computer close-by, without the lights off. Free of sentimentality like a Hindoo's religion.

I guess I dislike cinemas because I despise immersion. Immersion makes criticism impossible. Anything that seems to temporarily submerge you into its closed system feels like deception of the audience. Open world video games, Picasso, and jazz are the same way. They close you off

What D. Galkovsky said about educated authors posing as simple folksy peasants to avoid criticism being socially irresponsible applies to drug use trips too. The false objectivity of "experiences" (e.g. "religious experience" is an oxymoron) can never be critiqued like an essay.

I like one anecdote about the Guillermo del Toro guy claiming he saw an UFO and was disappointed at how cliche it looked, a classic metallic flying saucer that looked cheaply made and shiny, like a 1980s hoax summoned into reality. A very powerful attitude against the paranormal.

Dr. Ray Peat saying Picasso's empty cultural reputation as a genius made any criticism against him impossible, Col. Michael Aquino's poetry book that was revealed to him word by word by demons but still stylistically horrendous. None of them can be critiqued but all are mediocre.

Me: Foids. Can't live with them, can't live without them...
